1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,280
Containers are ephemeral, your database isn't, that's what persistent volumes solve.

2
00:00:08,280 --> 00:00:12,280
When a pod dies, its container file system is gone.

3
00:00:12,280 --> 00:00:18,360
For databases, caches and stateful apps, you need storage that outlives any pod.

4
00:00:18,360 --> 00:00:21,320
Kubernetes gives you two objects.

5
00:00:21,320 --> 00:00:27,440
A persistent volume is the actual storage, provisioned by an admin or dynamically by

6
00:00:27,440 --> 00:00:28,640
the cluster.

7
00:00:28,640 --> 00:00:32,840
A persistent volume claim is your request for storage.

8
00:00:32,840 --> 00:00:35,600
Kubernetes binds them one to one.

9
00:00:35,600 --> 00:00:39,440
Your pod mounts the claim, it doesn't care what's behind it.

10
00:00:39,440 --> 00:00:41,600
Two provisioning modes.

11
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:44,600
Static and admin pre-creates the PV.

12
00:00:44,600 --> 00:00:50,960
Dynamic, a storage class auto provisions one when the PVC is created, that's the modern

13
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:51,960
way.

14
00:00:51,960 --> 00:00:56,040
Pod dies, data stays, that's the contract.

15
00:00:56,040 --> 00:01:00,560
PV claims it, PV holds it, storage class provides it.

16
00:01:00,560 --> 00:01:04,000
Run the docs, Kubernetes, persistent volumes.

